Abstract: Commercial aviation enters the new year without any computer problems as midnight passes in Asia and Europe; about 1,350 commercial jets are in the air at the time, less than half the number of planes that flew last New Year's Eve (M)
Snippet: Commercial aviation enters the new year without any computer problems as midnight passes in Asia and Europe; about 1,350 commercial jets are in the air at the time, less than half the number of planes that flew last New Year's Eve (M)
LeadParagraph: Airports around the world, ordinarily quiet on New Year's Eve, were unusually so yesterday as thousands of potential travelers stayed put while the world's air traffic system rolled over to the year 2000.

Headline.Main: Fear of Computer Glitch Grounds Thousands of Air Travelers
Headline.PrintHeadline: 1/1/00: TECHNOLOGY AND 2000 -- MOMENTOUS RELIEF; Fear of Computer Glitch Grounds Thousands of Air Travelers
